I'm a little in shock that I still love these two as much as I did before.

*acknowledgmnt*
It's not the same love.

But I'm lit by the fact my heart still remembers HOW to love like this.

When magic seeps out along the fissures.

And things can still transform into new things.

I've cursed/blessed it since I grudg/lovingly got & watched the dvd, forced myself to open the wound in my heart, read the scriptbook & the book (again, for the Nth time).

It's like finding a long lost treasure... that you've outgrown... you expect its magic went off, stale...

So, I let go. 

Why didn't / I / ask?

I dropped just as many hints, lines, opens and check-ins as my person did.

The answer was always the same.

üêçüí´

This fandom hurts me so deeply.
Brings me back 10 years /worth/ of my life that I've not felt in the 10 years after let-go.

You can talk ALL you want about fighting for the... relationship... AND about having compassion for the issues that stop functionality.
(I *know*, I have that too! No, really, I was just as bad/worse.)

But we'd promised, and that was it.

That was our limit, the end, the stop.

I never got a goodbye.

I let go from a call w/my person, so I could deal w/fam emergency.

-gone-

I left my person messages, emails.

One last weeping voicemail that I'm not even sure was ever heard.

For weeks.

Then I had to live up to my promise that I would NOT reengage.

I waited.
I waited for some one's courage, to ask for what they wanted. Or, to ask for what they couldn't tolerate anylonger, to ask for it to stop.

Every conversation, every opened email, every voicemail, every sigh, every "we need to talk". Every awkward goodbye.

From 5,000 miles away, after 2-3 months of pleading.

I did not give up.

I let go.

Don't ask me to lie. I won't.

I know my person didn't want me at this distance, they weren't able to say they *wanted* from me at all.

And weren't able to ask for the *stop* either.

I let go.

But it's not, and it still works and it fits your new shape, even for an old thing.

It's discombobulating, and lovely, and terrifying.

Relationships like this are so achingly vital to humanity.

As husbands, it's cute.

As someone fighting for humanity... it's complicated.

It was hard to keep, stressful, satisfying, long, necessary, valued, hated on by fam, unspoken, sacred, shared, stuttered over, broken and mended twice, mess that we'd never been able to easily explain to anyone, including us-together. (Tho I think we both knew each ourselves.)

I used to argue about these two, and the ineffable husbands (a lot about them) and basically dissect what was cannon (some of which, from about 2005, I am still trying to find).
Enjoyed every fussy, hilarious moment of it, with someone I - had a similar relationship with... üòàüòá

I don't speak to this person anymore.
üñ§ü•Ä
